So tonight I'm driving around with 4 other friends in the car, and we decide to go past the movie theatre to see if anyone we know is around.  We go by, no one's there, so I turn around to go back home.  As I'm going past again, my friend, unbeknownst to me, opens the car door and hangs out and screaming jibberish--as a joke I guess but I had no idea he was doing it, he was sitting directly behind me.  Three seconds later a cop (who appeared to be vertical to us and had no idea of our speed) pulls me over and takes my license and registration and says that 'I was reckless driving and that I'm fully responsible for the person hanging out the car'.  He gives me a 300 dollar fine, and I get a citation for reckless driving in which he says I will most likely have my license suspended for 6 months.  On the citation sheet he claims I also ecelerated the speed limit of the parking lot, and yes, he spelled it ecelerated.  I know for a fact I went 28 miles per hour and that the parking lot speed limit is 25--but I also know from his position there was no way he could have calculated that difference as there was no radar or anything.  I was wondering if this was a just move on the cop's part?  I'm not looking for sympathy or anything, I just don't know the legality concerning driver's responsibility to the actions of other persons in the car that he was unaware of.  I live in Pennsylvania so the laws may be different, and I'm 16 so maybe he was just targetting me because I was young--but I don't believe a 6 month suspension is necessary.  Oh well, please reply if you have anything concerning the issue <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
